@government
go-to: menu

Sri Lanka, officially the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, is a semi-presidential republic with a powerful president and a parliament with somewhat constrained authority. The President serves as both head of state and head of government, wielding substantial executive power, while Parliament is responsible for legislation but operates under considerable presidential influence.

The President, modelled after the French president is elected by a ranked choice vote. The presidential term lasts six years, and the President can be re-elected. The role of the president extends far beyond ceremonial duties—the office possesses extensive governing powers including the authority to appoint the Prime Minister and Cabinet, dissolve Parliament at his discretion, and personally hold multiple ministerial portfolios. The President can govern through executive decree in many areas, bypassing Parliament and concentrating substantial decision-making authority in the presidency itself. The President also appoints provincial governors who represent the central government's authority in the regions.

Parliament consists of 196 members elected through a system of proportional representation, giving parties seats roughly proportional to their vote share in each electoral district. Elections operate with voters casting their ballots in multi-member electoral districts that correspond to the country's administrative districts. Parliamentary terms last six years unless dissolved earlier by the President. Parliament is responsible for passing legislation and can scrutinise government actions, though its ability to check presidential power is limited by the powers of the president.

Sri Lanka is divided into nine provinces, each headed by a governor appointed by the President. Below the provincial level, the country is organised into multiple administrative districts, each managed under the central government's authority. At the local level, governance is conducted through Municipal Councils, Urban Councils, and Village/Town Councils, responsible for local administration and services. 

