**Demographic Groups**

**Upper Class**: A small elite comprising industrialists, senior executives, and political leaders, often with inherited wealth and significant influence over economic and political spheres. They make up less than 1% of the population.

**Middle Class**: Professionals such as doctors, lawyers, teachers, and small business owners educated in former colonial schools, though economic changes began to strain their financial stability. They make up around 14% of the population.

**Working Class**: Manual laborers, factory workers, service employees and garment workers who often face low wages, limited job security, and challenging working conditions, leading to frequent labor unrest. They make up around 15% of the population.

**Rural**: Primarily engaged in agriculture, mining and fishing, they face issues like land fragmentation and inadequate infrastructure, remaining largely disconnected from economic growth benefits. They make up around 70% of the population. Within this grouping are the Indian Tamil estate workers who lack citizenship, work in abymsal conditions and earn meager wages, they make up around 5-7% of the population.

**Ethnic Groups**

**Sinhalese**: The islands largest ethnic group. Originally from North India, their ancestors migrated centuries ago. The Sinhalese speak Sinhala, an Indo-Aryan language. They are followers of Buddhism with a significant minority following Christianity. They generally live in the South, West and Central provinces with several communities and settlements in the North-East. Sinhalese parties have dominated the island's politics for decades and their politics is thus incredibly varied based on area, class, religon, etc split mainly between the UNP, SLFP, JVP, etc. They make up 73.95% of the population.

**Sri Lankan Tamil**: The islands second largest ethnic group. Part of the larger Tamil people originating from south India, their ancestors have lived on the island for just as long as the Sinhalese. They speak Tamil, a Dravidian language and are followers of Hinduism (Mostly Shaivism) with a large Christian minority. They dominate the North-East with communites in every major city. Traditionally, Tamils have supported pro-federal parties though some have began to drift towards seperatism and rebellion. They make up 12.71% of the population.

**Muslims**: The most genetically diverse group in Sri Lanka. From descendents of Yemenis, Malays, Tamils, Arabs, etc, They are united by their common religon of Islam. Speaking mostly Tamil, most can speak Sinhala as a second language. The Muslims are generally spread throughout the island with large pockets in major cities and the North-East. Despite maintaing a seperate cultural identity to other groups, they have generally supported Sinhalese parties like the SLFP and UNP. Recently there has been a shift towards Tamil parties or even a seperate political identity. They make up 7.05% of the population.

**Indian Tamil**: The youngest and more destitute of Sri Lanka. Descendent from lower caste Indian Tamil's brought by the british in the 19th century to farm first coffee, and then tea. They live mostly in the centre of the island in large slums close to their main occupation, the tea estates. Since independence the majority of them have no citizenship, with some being repatriated to India or Pakistan. The lack of franchisments has led them to suffer and politically, the few who can vote support the union and party CWC in the hopes of improving their lot. They make up around 5.51% of the population.

**Others**: This grouping consists of many groups such as the Burghers(Desendents of Europeans and theb locals), Kafirs(Desendents of African slaves and soliders brought by the Portugese), the ethnic Chinese and the indigeoneus "Vedda" whose history predates all other groups. The majority of this grouping reside in their own communities inside the major cities. This group makes up around 0.78% of the population.

